---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SchemaMap from '../../components/diagrams/SchemaMap.astro';
import SpokesHub from '../../components/diagrams/SpokesHub.astro';

const repo = 'https://github.com/riolly/bible-codex/blob/main';
---
<Layout title="Reference — Architecture Map · bible-codex" here="Reference · print-friendly" footer={false}>
  <p class="eyebrow">Reference · the one-page map</p>
  <h1>How bible-codex is shaped</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Four loosely-coupled data worlds that touch only through two bridges, and one coordinate —
    the Anchor — that everything user-made hangs on.
  </p>

  <div class="callout key">
    <span class="tag">The thesis in one breath</span>
    <p>
      The Bible <strong>text</strong> is read-only and shipped with the app.
      <strong>Your marks</strong> are separate, yours, and synced. They never touch directly —
      they meet only at <strong>scripture coordinates</strong>. That separation is what lets
      text be re-imported and marks still survive.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Four schemas, two bridges</h2>
  <figure>
    <SchemaMap />
    <figcaption>
      Adapted from <a href={`${repo}/data-architecture.md`}>data-architecture.md §1</a>. The
      two bridges (solid: Canonical Verse via the Anchor; dashed: Original Word via alignment)
      are the <em>only</em> way the worlds connect.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>What lands in each phase</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Phase</th><th>What the reader gets</th><th>Core tables</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P1</strong> Reading</td>
        <td>Beautiful genre-aware text; horizontal/vertical scroll; tunable layout</td>
        <td>translation · book · block · token · versification_map · layout_*</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P2</strong> Annotation</td>
        <td>Mark up like a physical Bible: highlight, note, connect, freehand ink</td>
        <td>layer · mark · note · connector · binding · ink_annotation · ink_stroke</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P3</strong> Lexicon</td>
        <td>Tap a word → Greek/Hebrew, Strong's, meaning; word study</td>
        <td>original_word · interlinear_alignment · lemma · strongs · morphology</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P4</strong> Advanced</td>
        <td>Portals, the reading Journey, themes/tags, research mode</td>
        <td><em>(none new — rides Anchor + Cross-reference)</em></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p style="font-size:0.98rem; color:var(--ink-soft);">
    The data model is <em>designed</em> for all four now, but each is <em>built</em> only when
    its phase arrives (<a
      href={`${repo}/docs/adr/0005-four-product-phases-design-all-build-in-order.md`}
      >ADR-0005</a
    >).
  </p>

  <h2>Translations are spokes, never wired together</h2>
  <figure>
    <SpokesHub />
    <figcaption>
      A KJV word and a BSB word are different objects. They relate transitively — by verse
      (coarse) or by the shared Greek/Hebrew word (fine). Never 1:1. (<a
        href={`${repo}/docs/adr/0001-three-layer-anchor-model.md`}>ADR-0001</a
      >)
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>The three seams that are locked forever</h2>
  <p>
    The repo's discipline: only <strong>three</strong> things are "migration-fatal." Lock
    these, and <em>don't over-design anything else.</em>
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Anchors key off coordinates</strong> (verse + word-index + optional Original-Word
      id), never internal DB ids — so the corpus stays freely re-importable.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Corpus = a token-stream + verse/block overlays</strong>, ingested from USFM
      (which carries the literary structure that makes genre-aware beauty possible).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Annotations are a scripture-anchored scene graph</strong>, never canvas
      coordinates.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p style="font-size:0.98rem; color:var(--ink-soft);">
    Everything else — sync backend, fonts, Markup styles, eraser rules, DB engine, exact
    translation set — is reversible. Don't bikeshed it. (<a
      href={`${repo}/OVERVIEW.md`}>OVERVIEW §4</a
    >)
  </p>

  <div class="lesson-footer">
    <div class="ask-teacher">
      <strong>This page is a map, not a lesson.</strong> Each box becomes its own lesson on the
      path. Ask your teacher to take any one of them next.
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
